Rating: 2
These--let's call them muffins--have the potential for being delicious. However, like many others, mine tasted like biscuits with a hint of coconut flavor. This was a test run for my sister's engagement party, so biscuits just won't cut it. I would suggest using vanilla extract instead of a vanilla bean. Cooks Illustrated has tested the quality that each gives to cake batters. Vanilla bean flavors work best in custards. The flavors tend to disappear in cake batters. I would use vanilla extract instead, and I would consider using cake flour to avoid the biscuit texture and aftertaste. Who knows how that will work with the coconut milk, but someone will try it :) I think I will use a coconut extract in a white cake mix to get a coconut flavor next time. I do like the look of the vanilla bean in the frosting, but it might be better to add the vanilla bean directly to the coconut milk once it is done boiling and begins the cooling process. It might absorb more of the flavors.

